definition.value: Any compound that has a nucleobase as a part.
Any straight-chain, C22 fatty acid having five C=C double bonds.
Any straight-chain, C22 fatty acid having four C=C double bonds.
A nucleotide having guanine as the base.
A  nucleotide having adenine as the base.
A purine ribonucleotide where the purine is guanine.
A purine riboncleotide where adenine is the purine.
A glycerate in which at least one of the hydroxy groups has been phosphorylated.

A steroid that has a structure based on a 21-carbon (pregnane) skeleton. Note that individual examples may have ring substituents at other positions and/or contain double bonds, aromatic A-rings, expanded/contracted rings etc., so the formula and mass may vary from that given for the generic structure.
A C20, straight-chain, polyunsaturated fatty acid anion containing five double bonds.
A dicarboxylate that contains four carbon atoms.
Any hydroxy carboxylic acid which contains a hydroxy group located beta- to the carboxylic acid group.
Any glycosphingolipid where the oligosaccharide component has an N-acetylgalactosaminyl residue at the non-reducing end.
A compound containing a sulfonic acid residue joined by a carbon-sulfur bond to a lipid.
A dihydroxy monocarboxylic acid consisting of phenylacetic acid having two phenolic hydroxy substituents.
A polymer, composed of polyanion macromolecules.
A ribonucleoside triphosphate oxoanion arising from global deprotonation of the  triphosphate groups of any nucleoside triphosphate; major species at pH 7.3.
Any saponin derived from a hydroxysteroid.
A steroid glycoside in which the steroid component is cholesterol.
An anion resulting from the removal of a proton from an organic sulfamic acid group.
Any cyclitol having one or more alcoholic hydroxy groups replaced by substituted or unsubstituted amino groups.
An organic heterotricyclic compound with a skeleton derived from a pyridine ring fused to an isoquinoline.
Any organic molecular entity derived from a fatty acid.
Any C20 polyunsaturated fatty acid having four double bonds and at least one oxo group.
A cyclodepsipeptide antibiotic, which is isolated from the filamentous fungus Aureobasidium pullulans R106 and is toxic to yeast at low concentrations (0.1-0.5 ug/ml).
An enzyme inhibitor that inhibits the action of inositol phosphorylceramide synthase.

A branched amino tetrasaccharide consisting of a sialyl residue, linked (2->3) to a galactosyl residue that in turn is linked (1->3) to a glucosaminyl residue, which is also carrying a fucosyl residue at the 4-position.
Any fatty aldehyde with one double or triple bond located at any position in the aliphatic chain.
Any substance that interacts with tubulin to inhibit polymerisation of microtubules.
Zwitterionic form of a polar amino acid having an anionic carboxy group and a protonated amino group.
Any donor that can transfer acyl groups between molecular entities.
A monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of nalidixic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
An alkanesulfonate in which the carbon at position 1 is attached to at least two hydrogens.
An organic cation resulting from the protonation of pyocyanin.
An alpha-amino-acid anion that is the conjugate base of S-sulfo-L-cysteine; major species ar pH 7.3.
An organophosphonate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of one of the two phosphonate OH groups of (1R,2S)-epoxypropylphosphonic acid; major species at pH 7.3.
A uridine-based nucleoside-peptide antibiotic which inhibits fungal chitin biosynthesis by inhibiting chitin synthase.
An organophosphonate oxoanion obtained by deprotonation of the two phosphonate OH groups of (1R,2S)-epoxypropylphosphonic acid.

A molecular messenger in which the molecule is specifically involved in transmitting information between cells. Such molecules are released from the cell sending the signal, cross over the gap between cells by diffusion, and interact with specific receptors in another cell, triggering a response in that cell by activating a series of enzyme controlled reactions which lead to changes inside the cell.
A quaternary ammonium ion that is the conjugate acid of sphingomyelin d18:1, obtined by protonation of the anionic phosphate function.
An ammonium ion that is obtained by protonation of the amino group of D-glucosylsphingosine. Major species at pH 7.3.
Any branched-chain fatty acid containing methyl branches only.
The dicarboxylic acid dianion formed from folic acid by loss of a proton from each of the two carboxy groups in the glutamic acid moiety.
The indol-3-yl carboxylic acid anion formed by loss of a proton from the carboxy group of (5-hydroxyindol-3-yl)acetic acid; principal microspecies at pH 7.3
Any organophosphate oxoanion that is a negatively charged phospholipid, e.g. phosphatidylserine(1-), phosphatidate(2-), phosphatidylglycerol(1-).
An ester where the ester linkage is bonded directly to an aromatic system.
An amide in which the amide linkage is bonded directly to an aromatic system.

An amino acid derivative resulting from reaction of tyrosine at the amino group or the carboxy group, any substitution of phenyl hydrogens, or from the replacement of any hydrogen of tyrosine by a heteroatom. The definition normally excludes peptides containing tyrosine residues.

A family of nitrogen molecular entities which are highly reactive and derived from nitric oxide (.NO) and superoxide (O2.(-)) produced via the enzymatic activity of inducible nitric oxide synthase 2 (NOS2) and NADPH oxidase respectively.
Any additive that enhances the efficiency of fuel.
